
[1]intemperance

   INTEM'PERANCE, n. [L. intemperantia.]

   1. In a general sense, want of moderation or due restraint; excess in
   any kind of action or indulgence; any exertion of body or mind, or any
   indulgence of appetites or passions which is injurious to the person or
   contrary to morality; as intemperance in study or in labor, in eating
   or drinking, or in any other gratification. Hence, appropriately and
   emphatically,

   2. Habitual indulgence in drinking spirituous liquors,with or without
   intoxication.

   Should a foreign army land on our shores, to levy such a tax upon us as
   intemperance levies--no mortal power could resist the swelling tide of
   indignation that would overwhelm it.
